shire, England"},"en":{"1230–":"1230–Deceased","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1260–Male":"1260–Deceased","1230–Male":"1230–Deceased","about 1260":"about 1260","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1230":"1230","1260":"1260","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hancock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name   Hann   + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-cok</i>, which was commonly added to personal names (see   Cocke  ).","Dutch: from Middle Dutch <i>hanecoc</i> ‘winkle, periwinkle’ (a type of shellfish), probably a metonymic occupational name for someone who gathered and sold shellfish.","History: Thomas Hancock, the uncle of Declaration of Independence signatory John Hancock (1736/7–93), was among the foremost of 18th-century American businessmen. He was a descendant of Nathaniel Hancock, who was known to have been in Cambridge, MA, as early as 1634. Born in Braintree, MA, John Hancock was president of the Second Continental Congress and the first governor of the state of MA."],"variants":[{"name":"Hancox","meanings":["English: variant of   Hancock  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Handcock","meanings":["English: variant of   Hancock   with intrusive <i>-d-</i>."]},{"name":"Hann","meanings":["German and Dutch: from a shortened pet form of the personal name <i>Johann</i> (see   John  ).","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Hann</i>, commonly a pet form of <i>Henry</i> (Middle English <i>Hanry</i>). <i>Hann</i> could also be a rhyming pet form of Randolph (Middle English <i>Randal</i>, shortened to <i>Ran</i> or <i>Rand</i>). <i>Han</i> was also a pet form of <i>Joh(a)n</i> in Middle Dutch, and it is possible that this usage was brought to England by Flemings after the Norman Conquest, but no evidence has yet been found that it was similarly used in Middle English. See   Henry   and   Randall  , and compare   Hankin  ,   Hancock  , and   Hanks  .","English: variant of   Ann   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":60,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":85,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Hancock was born in 1230, in Shropshire, England. He had at least 1 son with Mrs Thomas Hancock."},"et":{"1230–":"1230–Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1315":